      <div xml:id="NA103-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu poruḷvayiṉ pirinta talaivaṉ iṭaiccurattu āṟṟātu ākiya neñciṉaik kaḻaṟiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how HE who had separated for the sake of wealth grumbled with [his] heart that had become unable to bear it in the middle of the desert.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA103">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            oṉṟuterin turaittici ṉeñcē puṉkāṟ</l>
<l>            ciṟiyilai vēmpiṉ periya koṉṟu</l>
<l>            kaṭāaṅ cerukkiya kaṭuñciṉa muṉpiṟ</l>
<l>            kaḷiṟuniṉ ṟiṟanta nīra līrattup</l>
<l>            pālvī tōṉmulai yakaṭunilañ cērttip </l>
<l>            paciyaṭa muṭaṅkiya paiṅkaṭ cennāy</l>
<l>            māyā vēṭṭam pōkiya kaṇavaṉ</l>
<l>            poyyā marapiṟ piṇavuniṉain tiraṅkum</l>
<l>            viruntiṉ veṅkāṭṭu varuntutum yāmē</l>
<l>            yāḷviṉaik kakalvā meṉiṉu </l>
<l>            mīḷvā meṉiṉu nītuṇin tatuvē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent4">Having understood one thing,</l>
<l>heart, speak</l>
<l rend="indent4">– of what you have resolved: whether you say we return,</l>
<l rend="indent4">whether you say we depart for manly work.</l>
<l>We will suffer in the newly(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">viruntu</term>, here obviously not “feast” is the noun with obl. mark here used as an adverb (“of late a hot wilderness”)?</note> hot wilderness,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the green-eyed red dog, bent down to kill [its] hunger,</l>
<l rend="indent">pressing to the ground [its] belly with skinny breasts, milk ceased,</l>
<l rend="indent2">for the moisture that is not water coming in standing<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">niṉṟu</term> is syntactically problematic, since we have to read an anacoluthon: <term xml:lang="ta">kaḷiṟu</term> is subject of <term xml:lang="ta">niṉṟu</term>, but object of <term xml:lang="ta">iṟanta</term>.</note> from</l>
<l rend="indent2">the elephant bull, formerly with fierce anger, elated by must,</l>
<l rend="indent2">felling big [branches] of the small-leaved red-trunked Neem tree,</l>
<l rend="indent">is grieving, the husband gone for the unfailing hunt<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">māyā</term> according to T.V.G. something like 'unfailing', i.e. presumably not a noun but the neg. pey. to the verb <term xml:lang="ta">māy</term> 'to vanish'?</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">thinking of [its] female after [their] custom not to be betrayed.</l>
    </lg>
